The term '''acrites''' (frontiersman) is the transliteration of the [[Greek language|Greek]] word ''ακρίτης'', deriving from ''άκρα'' meaning edges - frontiers, being the Greek rendition of [[Latin]] ''limitaneus''. It first appears in the 10th century. [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] historian [[Constantine VII|Porphyrogenitos]] mentions that 

<center>"περιπατούσιν εμπρόσθεν του βασιλέως ακρίται πεντακόσιοι άνδρες εξωπλισμένοι".</center>

<center>"...ahead of the emperor marched 500 armed frontiersmen (acrites/ακρίτες)..."</center>

